The funniest part is that the major complaint (when you cut through the BS) is that folks are pissed that Wizards suddenly have the potential to farm drops and sell em.... yet no one cares when it's done to things like hounds.<br>
<br>
Their argument... well it's a Kunark dragon, and you can make major coin raping people who need the drops, bla bla bla.<br>
<br>
Yet that being said.... do the math....<br>
<br>
Nm... I'll do it... cause tanks are stoopid....<br>
<br>
(numbers are just aopproximations btw)<br>
<br>
4 dragons per week, with an average of 1-2 sellable drops (assuming Scale + CoF type of item... sellable at a modest 60k each.... cause wizzies are claiming to be &quot;fair&quot; ).  Assume 12 wizzies involved (2 groups of 6... since we know that the same group wont get all of the kills) AND assume that wizzies get all of the dragons and find buyers.<br>
<br>
120 * 4 dragons = 480k pp<br>
480k pp / 12 wizards = 40k each per week<br>
<br>
Now... note that each of these Wizards has to be 60 and have 23 or so AA points.<br>
<br>
Now let's look at Druids in WW... and hounds.  There are a ton of potential hounds... but lets say that there are only 4 that pop at a time... with a respawn of say 15 min.  And lets' say that only 1 in 4 hounds drop a pelt.  Right there, yer looking at 96 Pelt-dropping hounds a day or 672 pelts in a week.  <br>
<br>
672 pelts * 2k per pelt = 1344 per week.<br>
<br>
Now... We'll assume that our tree huggers need to sleep, so we'll say that there are 12 of em doing the farming.<br>
<br>
1344k per week / 12 druids = 112k per druid<br>
<br>
And note... the druids can do this in their mid 50s... no epic, no AA, no nada.<br>
<br>
Fek it... maybe the wizzies outta charge more.<br>
